Pros:
- very easy to support;
- compatibility with MySQL syntax;
- this #33584 get supported automatically;
- sometimes I write comments starting with `#` by mistake, and will be pleased if it worked;
- simplify creation of "quines".

Cons:
- it may be too bizarre to support all these styles of comments;
- PostgreSQL has [#>](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/14/functions-json.html) and similar operator due their own ugly quirks;
- it may interact worse with `m4` macro preprocessor;

Additional context:
- we can limit support for these comments by requiring whitespace after `#`;
- we can limit support for these comments by requiring it to be at the beginning of the line;

but MySQL supports all variants.

When I query an alias column of a merge-distributed table,  I got the following error: `Received exception from server (version 22.1.3): Code: 8. DB::Exception: Received from localhost:9000. DB::Exception: Cannot find column `id2` in source stream, there are only columns: [id]. (THERE_IS_NO_COLUMN)`

**How to reproduce**

ClickHouse server version: 22.1.3.7

```sql
CREATE TABLE part1_local (id Int32, id2 Int32 ALIAS id) ENGINE=Memory;
CREATE TABLE part2_local AS part1_local ENGINE=Memory;
CREATE TABLE merge_local (id Int32, id2 Int32) ENGINE=Merge(currentDatabase(), '^part.+_local$');

CREATE TABLE part1_all AS part1_local ENGINE=Distributed('cluster01', currentDatabase(), part1_local, rand());
CREATE TABLE part2_all AS part1_local ENGINE=Distributed('cluster01', currentDatabase(), part2_local, rand());
CREATE TABLE merge_all (id Int32, id2 Int32) ENGINE=Merge(currentDatabase(), '^part.+_all$');

INSERT INTO part1_local VALUES (1);
INSERT INTO part2_local VALUES (2);
```

```sql
> SELECT id, id2 FROM part1_local;
idid2
  1    1 

> SELECT id, id2 FROM part1_all;
idid2
  1    1 



> SELECT id, id2 FROM part2_local;
idid2
  2    2 

> SELECT id, id2 FROM part2_all;
idid2
  2    2 



> SELECT id, id2 FROM merge_local;
idid2
  1    1 

idid2
  2    2 


> SELECT id, id2 FROM merge_all;
Received exception from server (version 22.1.3):
Code: 8. DB::Exception: Received from localhost:9000. DB::Exception: Cannot find column `id2` in source stream,
there are only columns: [id]. (THERE_IS_NO_COLUMN)
```

```sql
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS a (a Int64) ENGINE=Memory;
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS b (a Int64) ENGINE=Memory;
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW IF NOT EXISTS mv1 TO b AS Select sleepEachRow(0.1) as a FROM a;
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW IF NOT EXISTS mv2 TO b AS Select sleepEachRow(0.1) as a FROM a;
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW IF NOT EXISTS mv3 TO b AS Select sleepEachRow(0.1) as a FROM a;
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW IF NOT EXISTS mv4 TO b AS Select sleepEachRow(0.1) as a FROM a;
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW IF NOT EXISTS mv5 TO b AS Select sleepEachRow(0.1) as a FROM a;

-- INSERT USING VALUES
INSERT INTO a VALUES(1);
SYSTEM FLUSH LOGS;

SELECT query_duration_ms >= 500
FROM system.query_log
WHERE
      current_database = currentDatabase()
  AND event_date >= yesterday()
  AND query LIKE '-- INSERT USING VALUES%'
  AND type = 'QueryFinish'
LIMIT 1;

WITH
(
    SELECT initial_query_id
    FROM system.query_log
    WHERE
            current_database = currentDatabase()
      AND event_date >= yesterday()
      AND query LIKE '-- INSERT USING VALUES%'
    LIMIT 1
) AS q_id
SELECT view_duration_ms >= 100
FROM system.query_views_log
WHERE initial_query_id = q_id;
```

This should return all 1's for the views since they are taking at the very least 100 ms to execute. Nevertheless, for 21.11+ all view_duration_ms are 0.

* 21.9.4.35: OK
* 21.10.4.26: OK
* 21.11.5.33: KO
* 21.12.2.17: KO
* 22.1.3.7: KO
* master: KO

Connected to ClickHouse server version 21.13.1 revision 54455.

```
